tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_polygon" title=3D"Dual polygon">Dual polyg=
on</a></th><td class=3D"infobox-data"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Isosceles_trapezoid" title=3D"Isosceles trapezoid">Isosceles trapezoid<=
/a></td></tr></tbody></table></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title=3D=
"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>, a <b>kite</b> is a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrilateral" title=3D"Quadrilateral">quadri=
lateral</a> with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflection_symmet=
ry" title=3D"Reflection symmetry">reflection symmetry</a> across a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diagonal" title=3D"Diagonal">diagonal</a>=
. Because of this symmetry, a kite has two equal angles and two pairs of ad=
jacent equal-length sides. Kites are also known as <b>deltoids</b>,<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-halsted_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-halsted-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but the word <i=
>deltoid</i> may also refer to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
eltoid_curve" title=3D"Deltoid curve">deltoid curve</a>, an unrelated geome=
tric object sometimes studied in connection with quadrilaterals.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-goormaghtigh_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-goormaghtigh-2"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K=
ite_(geometry)#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A kite may also be called a <b>dart<=
/b>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-charter-rogers_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-charter-rogers-4"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> particularly if it is not convex.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-gardner_5-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometr=
y)#cite_note-gardner-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-thurston_6-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cit=
e_note-thurston-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Every kite is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthodiago=
nal_quadrilateral" title=3D"Orthodiagonal quadrilateral">orthodiagonal quad=
rilateral</a> (its diagonals are at right angles) and, when convex, a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangential_quadrilateral" title=3D"Tang=
ential quadrilateral">tangential quadrilateral</a> (its sides are tangent t=
o an inscribed circle). The convex kites are exactly the quadrilaterals tha=
t are both orthodiagonal and tangential. They include as special cases the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_kite" title=3D"Right kite">r=
ight kites</a>, with two opposite right angles; the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombus" title=3D"Rhombus">rhombi</a>, with two diagonal =
axes of symmetry; and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square" =
title=3D"Square">squares</a>, which are also special cases of both right ki=
tes and rhombi.
</p><p>The quadrilateral with the greatest ratio of <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Perimeter" title=3D"Perimeter">perimeter</a> to <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diameter" title=3D"Diameter">diameter</a>=
 is a kite, with 60=C2=B0, 75=C2=B0, and 150=C2=B0 angles. Kites of two sha=
pes (one convex and one non-convex) form the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Prototile" title=3D"Prototile">prototiles</a> of one of the form=
s of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penrose_tiling" title=3D"=
Penrose tiling">Penrose tiling</a>. Kites also form the faces of several <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isohedral_figure" title=3D"Isohedral=
 figure">face-symmetric</a> polyhedra and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Tessellation" title=3D"Tessellation">tessellations</a>, and have be=
en studied in connection with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oute=
r_billiards" title=3D"Outer billiards">outer billiards</a>, a problem in th=
e advanced mathematics of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamica=
l_system" title=3D"Dynamical system">dynamical systems</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition_and_classificati=
on">Definition and classification</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DKite_(geometry)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Definition and classification"><span>edit</span></a><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Deltoid.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><i=
mg src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/Deltoid=
.svg/250px-Deltoid.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"153"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"839" data-file-height=3D"514"=
></a><figcaption>Convex and concave kites</figcaption></figure>
<p>A kite is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrilateral" titl=
e=3D"Quadrilateral">quadrilateral</a> with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Reflection_symmetry" title=3D"Reflection symmetry">reflection symm=
etry</a> across one of its diagonals. Equivalently, it is a quadrilateral w=
hose four sides can be grouped into two pairs of adjacent equal-length side=
s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-halsted_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-halsted-1"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-devilliers-adventures_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-devilliers-adventures-7=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> A kite can be constructed from the centers and crossing points=
 of any two intersecting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle" t=
itle=3D"Circle">circles</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-idiot_8-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-idio=
t-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Kites as described here may be either <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_polygon" title=3D"Convex polygon">convex</a> or =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concave_polygon" title=3D"Concave =
polygon">concave</a>, although some sources restrict <i>kite</i> to mean on=
ly convex kites. A quadrilateral is a kite <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/If_and_only_if" title=3D"If and only if">if and only if</a> any on=
e of the following conditions is true:
</p>
<ul><li>The four sides can be split into two pairs of adjacent equal-length=
 sides.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-devilliers-adventures_7-1" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-devillier=
s-adventures-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>One diagonal crosses the midpoint of the other diagonal at a right angl=
e, forming its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perpendicular_bisec=
tor" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Perpendicular bisector">perpendicular b=
isector</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-usiskin-griffin_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-usiskin-gr=
iffin-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> (In the concave case, the line through one of the diago=
nals bisects the other.)</li>
<li>One diagonal is a line of symmetry. It divides the quadrilateral into t=
wo congruent triangles that are mirror images of each other.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-devilliers-adventures_7-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-devilliers-adventures-7"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup></li>
<li>One diagonal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle_bisector" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Angle bisector">bisects</a> both of the angle=
s at its two ends.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-devilliers-adventures_7-3" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_not=
e-devilliers-adventures-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Kite quadrilaterals are named for the wind-blown, flying <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite" title=3D"Kite">kites</a>, which often have =
this shape<sup id=3D"cite_ref-beamer_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-beamer-10"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-alexander-koeberlein_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-alexander-koeb=
erlein-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> and which are in turn named for <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(bird)" title=3D"Kite (bird)">a hovering bird</a>=
 and the sound it makes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-nuncius_12-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-nunci=
us-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-liberman_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-liberman-1=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olaus_=
Henrici" title=3D"Olaus Henrici">Olaus Henrici</a>, the name "kite" was giv=
en to these shapes by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Joseph=
_Sylvester" title=3D"James Joseph Sylvester">James Joseph Sylvester</a>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-henrici_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-henrici-14"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Quadrilaterals can be classified <i>hierarchically</i>, meaning that=
 some classes of quadrilaterals include other classes, or <i>partitionally<=
/i>, meaning that each quadrilateral is in only one class. Classified hiera=
rchically, kites include the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhomb=
us" title=3D"Rhombus">rhombi</a> (quadrilaterals with four equal sides), <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Square (geometry)">squares</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-devilliers=
-role_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ki=
te_(geometry)#cite_note-devilliers-role-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apollonius_quadrilateral" title=3D"Apollonius qua=
drilateral">Apollonius quadrilaterals</a> (in which the products of opposit=
e sides are equal).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-harras_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-harras-16">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> All <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equilateral_polygo=
n" title=3D"Equilateral polygon">equilateral</a> kites are rhombi, and all =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equiangular_polygon" title=3D"Equi=
angular polygon">equiangular</a> kites are squares. When classified partiti=
onally, rhombi and squares would not be kites, because they belong to a dif=
ferent class of quadrilaterals; similarly, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Right_kite" title=3D"Right kite">right kites</a> discussed bel=
ow would not be kites. The remainder of this article follows a hierarchical=
 classification; rhombi, squares, and right kites are all considered kites.=
 By avoiding the need to consider special cases, this classification can si=
mplify some facts about kites.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-devilliers-role_15-1" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#c=
ite_note-devilliers-role-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Like kites, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram=
" title=3D"Parallelogram">parallelogram</a> also has two pairs of equal-len=
gth sides, but they are opposite to each other rather than adjacent. Any <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_polygon" title=3D"Simple poly=
gon">non-self-crossing</a> quadrilateral that has an axis of symmetry must =
be either a kite, with a diagonal axis of symmetry; or an <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isosceles_trapezoid" title=3D"Isosceles trapezoid">=
isosceles trapezoid</a>, with an axis of symmetry through the midpoints of =
two sides. These include as special cases the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Rhombus" title=3D"Rhombus">rhombus</a> and the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rectangle" title=3D"Rectangle">rectangle</a> respe=
ctively, and the square, which is a special case of both.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-halsted_1-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-halsted-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The self-crossing quadrila=
terals include another class of symmetric quadrilaterals, the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiparallelogram" title=3D"Antiparallelogram">=
antiparallelograms</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-alsina-nelson_17-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-=
alsina-nelson-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
