a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reuleaux_triangle" title=3D"Reul=
eaux triangle">Reuleaux triangle</a></div></div><div class=3D"tsingle" styl=
e=3D"width:180px;max-width:180px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height=
:151px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/File:Lute_of_Pythagoras.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><=
img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/=
ad/Lute_of_Pythagoras.svg/250px-Lute_of_Pythagoras.svg.png" decoding=3D"asy=
nc" width=3D"178" height=3D"151" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"1905" data-file-height=3D"1621"></a></span></div><div class=3D"thumbcap=
tion"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lute_of_Pythagoras" title=3D=
"Lute of Pythagoras">Lute of Pythagoras</a></div></div></div></div></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_kite" title=3D"Right =
kite">right kites</a> have two opposite <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Right_angle" title=3D"Right angle">right angles</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-devilliers-role_15-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-devilliers-role-15"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-alsina-nelson_17-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-alsina-nelson-17"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The right kites are exactly the kites that are <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Cyclic_quadrilateral" title=3D"Cyclic quadrilateral">cyclic q=
uadrilaterals</a>, meaning that there is a circle that passes through all t=
heir vertices.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-gant_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-gant-18"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> The cyclic quadrilaterals may equivalently defined as the quadrilaterals=
 in which two opposite angles are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Supplementary_angles" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Supplementary angles">=
supplementary</a> (they add to 180=C2=B0); if one pair is supplementary the=
 other is as well.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-usiskin-griffin_9-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-usis=
kin-griffin-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> Therefore, the right kites are the kites with two=
 opposite supplementary angles, for either of the two opposite pairs of ang=
les. Because right kites circumscribe one circle and are inscribed in anoth=
er circle, they are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bicentric_quad=
rilateral" title=3D"Bicentric quadrilateral">bicentric quadrilaterals</a> (=
actually tricentric, as they also have a third circle externally tangent to=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_side" title=3D"Exten=
ded side">extensions of their sides</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-alsina-nelson_=
17-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(ge=
ometry)#cite_note-alsina-nelson-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> If the sizes of an inscribe=
d and a circumscribed circle are fixed, the right kite has the largest area=
 of any quadrilateral trapped between them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-josefsson-ar=
ea_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_=
(geometry)#cite_note-josefsson-area-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Among all quadrilaterals, the shape that has the greatest ratio of i=
ts <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perimeter" title=3D"Perimeter">=
perimeter</a> to its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diameter" tit=
le=3D"Diameter">diameter</a> (maximum distance between any two points) is a=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equidiagonal_quadrilateral" titl=
e=3D"Equidiagonal quadrilateral">equidiagonal</a> kite with angles 60=C2=B0=
, 75=C2=B0, 150=C2=B0, 75=C2=B0. Its four vertices lie at the three corners=
 and one of the side midpoints of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Reuleaux_triangle" title=3D"Reuleaux triangle">Reuleaux triangle</a>.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-ball_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-ball-20"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-griffiths-culpin_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-griffiths-culpin-21"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 An equidiagonal kite is a special case of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Midsquare_quadrilateral" title=3D"Midsquare quadrilateral">midsq=
uare quadrilateral</a>. When an equidiagonal kite has side lengths less tha=
n or equal to its diagonals, like this one or the square, it is one of the =
quadrilaterals with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biggest_li=
ttle_polygon" title=3D"Biggest little polygon">greatest ratio of area to di=
ameter</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-audet-hansen-svrtan_22-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-audet-=
hansen-svrtan-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A kite with three 108=C2=B0 angles and one 36=C2=B0 angle forms the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_hull" title=3D"Convex hull"=
>convex hull</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lute_of_Py=
thagoras" title=3D"Lute of Pythagoras">lute of Pythagoras</a>, a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractal" title=3D"Fractal">fractal</a> made =
of nested <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagram" title=3D"Pent=
agram">pentagrams</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-darling_23-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-darling=
-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> The four sides of this kite lie on four of the sides of a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_pentagon" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Regular pentagon">regular pentagon</a>, with a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_triangle_(mathematics)" title=3D"Golden =
triangle (mathematics)">golden triangle</a> glued onto the fifth side.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-alsina-nelson_17-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-alsina-nelson-17"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Aperiodic_monotile_smith_2023.svg" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/b/bf/Aperiodic_monotile_smith_2023.svg/250px-Aperiodic_monotile_s=
mith_2023.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"211" class=3D=
"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"510" data-file-height=3D"431"></a><fig=
caption>Part of an aperiodic tiling with prototiles made from eight kites</=
figcaption></figure>
<p>There are only eight polygons that can tile the plane such that reflecti=
ng any tile across any one of its edges produces another tile; this arrange=
ment is called an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edge_tessellatio=
n" title=3D"Edge tessellation">edge tessellation</a>. One of them is a tili=
ng by a right kite, with 60=C2=B0, 90=C2=B0, and 120=C2=B0 angles. It produ=
ces the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deltoidal_trihexagonal_til=
ing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Deltoidal trihexagonal tiling">deltoida=
l trihexagonal tiling</a> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kit=
e_(geometry)#Tilings_and_polyhedra">=C2=A7&nbsp;Tilings and polyhedra</a>).=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-kirby-umble_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-kirby-umble-24"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prototile" title=3D"Prototile=
">prototile</a> made by eight of these kites tiles the plane only <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aperiodic_tiling" title=3D"Aperiodic tili=
ng">aperiodically</a>, key to a claimed solution of the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Einstein_problem" title=3D"Einstein problem">einstein=
 problem</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-smkg_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-smkg-25"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-Euclidean_geometry" =
title=3D"Non-Euclidean geometry">non-Euclidean geometry</a>, a kite can hav=
e three right angles and one non-right angle, forming a special case of a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lambert_quadrilateral" title=3D"Lam=
bert quadrilateral">Lambert quadrilateral</a>. The fourth angle is acute in=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_geometry" title=3D"Hyp=
erbolic geometry">hyperbolic geometry</a> and obtuse in <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_geometry" title=3D"Spherical geometry">sphe=
rical geometry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-eves_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-eves-26"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Properties">Properties</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKite_(geometry)&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Properties"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Diagonals,_angles,_and_area=
"><span id=3D"Diagonals.2C_angles.2C_and_area"></span>Diagonals, angles, an=
d area</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKite_=
(geometry)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Diagon=
als, angles, and area"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Every kite is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthodiagonal_=
quadrilateral" title=3D"Orthodiagonal quadrilateral">orthodiagonal quadrila=
teral</a>, meaning that its two diagonals are <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Perpendicular" title=3D"Perpendicular">at right angles</a> to e=
ach other. Moreover, one of the two diagonals (the symmetry axis) is the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perpendicular_bisector" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Perpendicular bisector">perpendicular bisector</a> of th=
e other, and is also the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle_bis=
ector" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Angle bisector">angle bisector</a> of=
 the two angles it meets.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-halsted_1-3" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-halst=
ed-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> Because of its symmetry, the other two angles of the kite =
must be equal.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-beamer_10-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-beamer-10"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-alexander-koeberlein_11-1" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-alexander=
-koeberlein-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> The diagonal symmetry axis of a convex kite div=
