ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A kite with angles 60=C2=B0, 90=C2=B0, 120=C2=B0, 90=C2=B0 can also =
tile the plane by repeated reflection across its edges; the resulting tesse=
llation, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deltoidal_trihexagona=
l_tiling" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Deltoidal trihexagonal tiling">del=
toidal trihexagonal tiling</a>, superposes a tessellation of the plane by r=
egular hexagons and isosceles triangles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-alsina-nelson_1=
7-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geo=
metry)#cite_note-alsina-nelson-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Deltoidal_icositetrahedron" title=3D"Deltoidal icositetrah=
edron">deltoidal icositetrahedron</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Deltoidal_hexecontahedron" title=3D"Deltoidal hexecontahedron">deltoid=
al hexecontahedron</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapez=
ohedron" title=3D"Trapezohedron">trapezohedron</a> are <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyhedra" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polyhedra">p=
olyhedra</a> with congruent kite-shaped <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Face_(geometry)" title=3D"Face (geometry)">faces</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-grunbaum_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-grunbaum-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which can alternati=
vely be thought of as tilings of the sphere by congruent spherical kites.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-sakano-akama_38-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-sakano-akama-38"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> There are infinitely many <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isohe=
dral_figure" title=3D"Isohedral figure">face-symmetric tilings</a> of the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_plane" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Hyperbolic plane">hyperbolic plane</a> by kites.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-dunham-lindgren-witte_39-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-dunham-lindgren-witte-39"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> These polyhedra (equivalently, spherical tilings), the square and=
 deltoidal trihexagonal tilings of the Euclidean plane, and some tilings of=
 the hyperbolic plane are shown in the table below, labeled by <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Face_configuration" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Face configuration">face configuration</a> (the numbers of neighbors o=
f each of the four vertices of each tile). Some polyhedra and tilings appea=
r twice, under two different face configurations.
</p>
