<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezohedron" title=3D"Tra=
pezohedron">trapezohedra</a> are another family of polyhedra that have cong=
ruent kite-shaped faces. In these polyhedra, the edges of one of the two si=
de lengths of the kite meet at two "pole" vertices, while the edges of the =
other length form an equatorial zigzag path around the polyhedron. They are=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_polyhedron" title=3D"Dua=
l polyhedron">dual polyhedra</a> of the uniform <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Antiprism" title=3D"Antiprism">antiprisms</a>.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-grunbaum_37-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-grunbaum-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A commonly seen ex=
ample is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagonal_trapezohed=
ron" title=3D"Pentagonal trapezohedron">pentagonal trapezohedron</a>, used =
for ten-sided <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dice" title=3D"Dice"=
>dice</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-alsina-nelson_17-7" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-alsina-nelson=
-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Outer_billiards">Outer bill=
iards</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKite_(=
geometry)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Outer b=
illiards"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<p>Mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Schwartz_=
(mathematician)" title=3D"Richard Schwartz (mathematician)">Richard Schwart=
z</a> has studied <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outer_billiard" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Outer billiard">outer billiards</a> on kites=
. Outer billiards is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamical_s=
ystem" title=3D"Dynamical system">dynamical system</a> in which, from a poi=
nt outside a given <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compact_set" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Compact set">compact</a> <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_set" title=3D"Convex set">convex set</a> in the =
plane, one draws a tangent line to the convex set, travels from the startin=
g point along this line to another point equally far from the point of tang=
ency, and then repeats the same process. It had been open since the 1950s w=
hether any system defined in this way could produce paths that get arbitrar=
ily far from their starting point, and in a 2007 paper Schwartz solved this=
 problem by finding unbounded billiards paths for the kite with angles 72=
=C2=B0, 72=C2=B0, 72=C2=B0, 144=C2=B0, the same as the one used in the Penr=
ose tiling.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-schwartz-unbounded_40-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)#cite_note-schwart=
z-unbounded-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> He later wrote a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Monograph" title=3D"Monograph">monograph</a> analyzing outer bil=
liards for kite shapes more generally. For this problem, any <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affine_transformation" title=3D"Affine transform=
ation">affine transformation</a> of a kite preserves the dynamical properti=
es of outer billiards on it, and it is possible to transform any kite into =
a shape where three vertices are at the points <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=
=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><=
math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle=
 (-1,0)}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
